of geographical knowledge, the material conditions of travel, and the variety of destinations that sought to profit from visitors with money to spend. Entrepreneurs began to transform the critical steps of travel-deciding where to go and how to get there-into commodities that could be produced in volume and sold to a marketplace of consumers. The identities of Americans prosperous enough to afford such commodities were fundamentally changed as they came to define themselves through the consumption of experiences.Mackintosh ultimately demonstrates that the cultural values and market forces surrounding tourism in the early nineteenth century continue to shape our experience of travel to this day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jun 2020) 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aTourismxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aTouristszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aTravelerszUnited Statesy19th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479833146423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479833146.jpg  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK